questions.text:
What does the `?` after `age` mean in this interface?

```typescript
interface User {
    name: string;
    age?: number;
}
```

What does this generic function do?

```typescript
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
    return arg;
}

const result = identity<string>("hello");
```

questions.explanation:
`<T>` is a **type parameter** — a placeholder filled in at call time. The function works for any type while preserving type information:

```typescript
function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
    return arg;
}

const s = identity<string>("hello");  // type: string
const n = identity<number>(42);       // type: number
const b = identity(true);             // type inferred: boolean

// Unlike `any`, generics keep type safety:
// identity<string>(42);  // Error: number is not assignable to string
```

questions.text:
What is printed by this code?

```typescript
const user = {
    profile: {
        city: "Warsaw"
    }
};

console.log(user?.profile?.city);
```

questions.explanation:
**Optional chaining** (`?.`) safely accesses nested properties. If any step is `null` or `undefined`, the whole expression short-circuits to `undefined` instead of throwing:

```typescript
const user = { profile: { city: "Warsaw" } };

console.log(user?.profile?.city);   // "Warsaw" — all properties exist

const empty = {};
console.log(empty?.profile?.city);  // undefined — safe, no error

// Without optional chaining:
console.log(empty.profile.city);    // TypeError: Cannot read property 'city'
```

